<TITLE> Regional energy management system stressed </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 28 (bdnews24.com)--The prime minister's economic affair adviser has said south Asia can attain faster pace of development with a coordinated energy management system. "Some south Asian countries have huge power generation capacity with limited scope of consumption. But Bangladesh and India have great demand for the resources. All theses countries can benefit if there is a coordinated energy management system," said Dr Moshiur Rahman. He made the remark at a discussion at Dhaka University's Faculty of Business Studies on Friday. Bangladesh Bank governor Atiur Rahman, former governor Salehuddin Ahmed, Centre for Policy Dialogue executive director Mustafizur Rahman and Dhaka University vice-chancellor AAMS Arefin Siddique also addressed the function. Atiur said Bangladesh has proved its ability by maintaining the development pace during the economic recession. "Now the economy will be able to attain faster development if supply of basic things like power and energy is ensured." Salehuddin suggested publication of price lists of imported goods in the media as a means to control inflation. Mustafizur said China's economy would surpass that of the United States and India would be world's third largest economy in two decades. "Bangladesh has to get ready if it wants to benefit from that situation," he added. Siddique mentioned that a third of the world's population go to sleep without dinner. "The number of such people in Bangladesh is also huge. We've to take into consideration this reality in all our economic policymaking." bd
